<subSubSection pageId="46" pageNumber="1005" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="46.[151,1058,287,397]" pageId="46" pageNumber="1005">
D i a g n o s i s: The genus 
<emphasis box="[457,540,288,309]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="1005">Isoparis</emphasis>
OPITZ was described in 2017 (
<bibRefCitation author="OPITZ W" box="[854,977,287,309]" pageId="46" pageNumber="1005" pagination="29 - 117" refId="ref53721" refString="OPITZ W. (2017): Classification, natural history, and evolution of the of the subfamily Peloniinae OPITZ (Coleoptera: Cleroidea: Cleridae). Part VII. The World genera of Peloniinae (Coleoptera: Cleridae). - Linzer biologische Beitrage 49 (1): 29 - 117." type="journal article" year="2017">OPITZ 2017</bibRefCitation>
). In this work, I described 
<emphasis box="[359,549,317,338]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="1005">Isoparis virgulata</emphasis>
from which 
<emphasis box="[704,827,317,338]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="1005">I. cassidilis</emphasis>
specimens differ by showing a more oblong pronotum, more fully developed pronotal tubercles, and the visible abdominal sternites II-IV each show a pair of small bursae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="46" pageNumber="1005" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="46.[151,1059,413,669]" pageId="46" pageNumber="1005">
D e s c r i p t i o n: Size: Length 
<quantity box="[516,597,413,434]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.3" pageId="46" pageNumber="1005" unit="mm" value="4.3">4.3 mm</quantity>
; width 1.0 mm. Form: As in 
<figureCitation box="[895,980,413,435]" captionStart="Figs 326-329" captionStartId="109.[151,191,1519,1541]" captionTargetBox="[153,1061,195,1498]" captionTargetId="figure@109.[153,1061,195,1501]" captionTargetPageId="109" captionText="Figs 326-329: Habitus; (326) Cregya triguttata; (327) C. vicosa; (328) Eurycaulis anaxcis; (329) Isoparis cassidilis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746824" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746824/files/figure.png" pageId="46" pageNumber="1005">Fig. 329</figureCitation>
. Color: Cranium and pronotum castaneous, pronotal disc with 3 black stripes; pterothorax brown; mesothorax, metathorax, and abdomen brown; elytra mostly castaneous, with yellow X-shaped marking; legs testaceous. Head: Eyes large, coarsely facetted, eye wider than frons (EW/FW 25/20); funicular antennomeres subfiliform (
<figureCitation box="[876,951,530,552]" captionStart="Figs 92-100" captionStartId="74.[151,191,872,894]" captionTargetBox="[175,1038,229,838]" captionTargetId="figure@74.[155,1062,203,862]" captionTargetPageId="74" captionText="Figs 92-100: Antennae; (92) Pyticeroides desodes; (93) Ichnea cerinis; (94) Agnatis vaurieae; (95) Ampleris amazon; (96) Nepsudia guenda; (97) Isoparis cassidilis; (98) Pelonium atrigonatium; (99) Aphelocerus yaguare; (100) Madoniella selvanegra." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746754" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746754/files/figure.png" pageId="46" pageNumber="1005">Fig. 97</figureCitation>
), capitular antennomeres 9 and 10 triangular, antennomere 11 narrow ovate. Thorax: Pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[159,248,589,611]" captionStart="Figs 163-170" captionStartId="79.[151,191,1521,1543]" captionTargetBox="[183,1039,199,1493]" captionTargetId="figure@79.[151,1059,199,1508]" captionTargetPageId="79" captionText="Figs 163-170: Pronota; (163) Artoadenus atrafinus; (164) Cregya triguttula; (165) C. biguttula; (166) Perilypus schusteri (167) Platynoptera potaro; (168) Pelonium erudiatum; (169) Parapelonides aodontus; (170) Isoparis cassidilis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746764" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746764/files/figure.png" pageId="46" pageNumber="1005">Fig. 170</figureCitation>
) oblong, lateral tubercle well defined (PW/PL 65/74), disc coarsely punctate; elytral asetiferous punctures profusely distributed; (EL/EW 185/50). Abdomen: Pygidium quadrate 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[343,350,647,669]" pageId="46" pageNumber="1005">/</emphasis>
scutiform; aedeagus as in 
<figureCitation box="[613,701,647,669]" captionStart="Figs 243-248" captionStartId="90.[151,191,1268,1290]" captionTargetBox="[153,1061,198,1253]" captionTargetId="figure@90.[153,1061,198,1253]" captionTargetPageId="90" captionText="Figs 243-248: Aedeagi; (243) Pelonium falcatum; (244) Nepsudia guenda; (245) Katacompsus jubatus; (246) Isoparis cassidilis; (247) Pujoliclerus abditus; (248) Pujoliclerus ariquemes." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746786" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746786/files/figure.png" pageId="46" pageNumber="1005">Fig. 246</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="46.[151,1059,684,736]" pageId="46" pageNumber="1005">
Variation: Length 4.0-5.0 mm; width 
<quantity box="[551,675,685,706]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.55" metricValueMax="1.8" metricValueMin="1.3" pageId="46" pageNumber="1005" unit="mm" value="1.55" valueMax="1.8" valueMin="1.3">1.3-1.8 mm</quantity>
. Other than body size, the available specimens are quite homogeneous.
</paragraph>
